english:
  title: A Letter to Damji
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I bow respectfully before you, Damji. Your letter of instruction has brought me such shame that I have read it through twice and thrice, my heart contracting with remorse. Yet know this—all of this stems from your great love for me, your high regard for my person. The deeper your kindness, the more easily resentment takes root between us. Such is the nature of things.

    We have been companions for long years. You know well the principles by which I live. Though I was once hasty and proud, earning the disdain of many, I have in time learned through bitter experience to bend my pride and walk a different path. I have studied to be square within yet round without—to bow before ordinary men, to keep silent with head bowed, to seem unable to speak, believing this might spare me the world's displeasure. Yet if I can bear the words of common folk, how is it I cannot bear a single word from you? You should understand this and refrain from blame. But now your letter comes with measured courtesy concealing reproof, and my offense seems grave—while your way of treating others seems rather narrow, does it not?

    Is it not because I have grown poor and withered, because the world has turned its back and fled, that you too now regret your former acquaintance with me? You find no great fault in me, yet cannot bring yourself to abandon me cleanly. You await only some small pretext to sever our bond. And is this not the way of the world? Men rise from poverty to prominence in a single day, and their feelings shift like clouds. They forget their old friends, satisfied with their new station. Would you call such men virtuous? I did not imagine that one of your righteous bearing would act thus. If you truly wish to part from me, what difficulty lies in it?

    I am now reduced to the uttermost poverty. Soon I shall withdraw into deep seclusion, far from the world's notice. Then our paths will diverge, and my footsteps will trouble your courtyard no more. Though you do not push me away, I shall remove myself. You need not seek my faults or fear our bond will not be broken. My ailment grows daily more severe, and I am weary beyond measure. I cannot write more. I submit this with great trepidation and respect.
  footnotes:
    - 'Damji (湛之): The recipient''s courtesy name; the full identity remains unclear from the text alone.'
    - 'Square within yet round without (方其中圓其外): A reference to the Daoist principle of adapting one''s inner nature to external circumstances.'
    - The ailment mentioned (痞病) likely refers to both physical and emotional distress, suggesting the author's state of both bodily and spiritual affliction.
